    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The only reagent that will “pick out” a primary aromatic amine (aniline) but not a secondary one (N-methylaniline) is the carbylamine test:</p>\n<p>• Carbylamine test (Option D: CHCl₃ + alcoholic KOH)  </p>\n<p>– RNH₂ + CHCl₃ + 3 KOH → R–NC (isocyanide, foul smell) + 3 KCl + 3 H₂O  </p>\n<p>– Only primary amines give the isocyanide; secondary amines (like N-methylaniline) do not react.</p>\n<p>Options A, B and C all react (or fail to react) with both aniline and N-methylaniline in essentially the same way, so they cannot be used to tell the two apart.</p>",
