  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Which of the following is least soluble in water at $$298 \\mathrm{~K}$$ ?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{NH}_2$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\mathrm{N}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\mathrm{NH}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NH}_2$$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Aniline $$(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NH}_2)$$ is least soluble in water at $$298 \\mathrm{~K}$$ due to the presence of high molecular mass benzene ring present in ring. Lower aliphatic amines such as $$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{NH}_2,\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\mathrm{~N}$$ and $$(\\mathrm{CH}_3)_2 \\mathrm{NH}$$ can form intermolecular hydrogen bonds with water molecules and hence soluble in water. Solubility of amines decreases with increase in molar mass due to increase in the hydrophobic part which retard the formation of $$\\mathrm{H}$$-bonds.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2019,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>If aniline is treated with $$1: 1$$ mixture of conc. $$\\mathrm{HNO}_3$$ and conc. $$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{SO}_4$$, p-nitroaniline and $$m$$-nitroaniline are formed nearly in equal amounts. This is due to</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$$m$$-directing property of $$-\\mathrm{NH}_2$$ group\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "protonation of $$-\\mathrm{NH}_2$$ which causes deactivation of benzene ring\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$$m$$ and $$p$$ directing property of $$-\\mathrm{NH}_2$$ group\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "isomerisation of some $$p$$-nitroaniline into $$m$$-nitroaniline"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "B"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>On treatment of aniline with $$1: 1$$ mixture of conc. $$\\mathrm{HNO}_3$$ and conc. $$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{SO}_4$$, $$p$$-nitro aniline and $$m$$-nitro aniline are formed nearly in equal amounts. This is due to protonation of $$-\\mathrm{NH}_2$$ which causes deactivation of benzene ring. Under strongly acidic medium, aniline is protonated to form anilinium ion which in $$m$$-directing.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lttmb90b/bf33f575-7197-4cf4-a68f-7bc5d1ab894c/e07ae2b0-e351-11ee-9d92-fb7ecc87d51a/file-1lttmb90c.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lttmb90b/bf33f575-7197-4cf4-a68f-7bc5d1ab894c/e07ae2b0-e351-11ee-9d92-fb7ecc87d51a/file-1lttmb90c.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Compounds Containing Nitrogen Question 11 English Explanation\"></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2019,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "During the fusion of organic compound with sodium metal, nitrogen present in the organic compound is converted into\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$\\mathrm{NaNO}_2$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$\\mathrm{NaNH}_2$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "NaCN\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "NaNC"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>When an organic compound containing nitrogen is fused with sodium metal—a procedure known as the sodium fusion test or Lassaigne's test—the nitrogen is transformed into a water-soluble salt. In this test, the conditions favor the formation of the cyanide ion. When the fused mass is dissolved in water, the nitrogen present is converted into sodium cyanide, which is written as:</p>\n<p>$$\\mathrm{NaCN}$$</p>\n<p>This is the basis for subsequent confirmatory tests (such as the formation of Prussian blue when the solution is treated with ferrous sulfate). </p>\n<p>Thus, the correct answer is:</p>\n<p>Option C: $$\\mathrm{NaCN}.$$</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2018,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2018",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
